article.description: The Phoenix earned an automatic bid to the tournament Sunday by winning their second straight Horizon League tournament.
article.headline: Phoenix earn another shot at NCAA Tournament
article.linkText: Wisc.-Green Bay wins second straight Horizon tourney
article.story:
GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- With the most victories in school
history, Wisconsin-Green Bay is ready to win its first NCAA
tournament game.

	   The Phoenix earned an automatic bid to the tournament Sunday by
winning their second straight Horizon League tournament.

	   Kristy Loiselle and Natalie Yudt scored 17 points each as the Phoenix (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) won their fifth tournament title in six years with
an 83-59 victory over Detroit.

	   Next up, the NCAA tournament, where the Phoenix (27-3) have
never won in six previous appearances.

	   "We're here,'' Phoenix coach Kevin Borseth said. "We've got a
good squad, obviously. We're not going to be taken lightly.''

	   Wisconsin-Green Bay beat a conference opponent on its home court
for the 40th straight time and knocked off Detroit (10-20) in the
championship for the second straight year.

	   The Phoenix, who beat the Titans for the 15th straight time
overall, are 22-4 in the tournament.

	   Loiselle, the tournament's most valuable player, had 12 of her
points in the first half. Chandra Johnson finished with 15 points
and Sara Boyer added 11.

	   "I think they still should be a top 16 team right now, that's
why I think they deserve a four seed at least, and seven at the
very lowest,'' Detroit coach Anne Rexford said.

	   Wisconsin-Green Bay missed its first four shots of the game but
regrouped and went on a 20-4 run to take a 28-12 lead.

	   Detroit closed the gap with a 9-4 burst late in the half. Caitie
Goddard hit a jumper with 1 second left to make it 38-27.

	   "I don't think we came out to a fast start,'' Loiselle said.
"There were a few opportunities where I thought I needed to be
aggressive, so I took it the first half. The second half we were
able to move the ball around the floor and find more openings.''

	   Yudt, who had 15 second-half points, scored eight in a 14-7 run
after the intermission to give the Phoenix a 52-34 lead. The Titans
never got closer than 16 points the rest of the way.

	   Lori Wild led Detroit with 12 points.

	   Wisconsin-Green Bay set a team record for victories since
joining Division I in 1987-88. The previous record of 24 wins was
set last season.

	   The Phoenix will learn whom they play in the NCAA tournament
when the pairings are announced March 16.

	   "It doesn't make a whole lot of difference,'' Borseth said. "I
don't think we're going to be playing Connecticut the first game,
but I do know I'd like to play them at some point because, if we
do, that means that we've advanced a couple of games.''
